      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        The Cooling-Off Period When Buying and Selling Property in Queensland
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Queensland gives buyers a 5-business-day window to reconsider after signing a contract. Understanding exactly how it works and what it costs to use it matters whether you are buying or selling.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>In Queensland, residential property buyers are entitled to a cooling-off period after signing a contract for the sale of a home. This is a statutory right under the <em>Property Occupations Act 2014 (Qld)</em> and it exists to give buyers who have signed under pressure, or without the benefit of legal advice at the time of signing, a window to reconsider. For sellers, understanding what triggers this period, what it costs a buyer to exercise it, and the scenarios where it does not apply is important context for how you negotiate and structure a sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the cooling-off period works</h2>
      <p>The cooling-off period in Queensland runs for 5 business days. It begins on the day the buyer receives a copy of the signed contract, or the day the contract is signed by the buyer if they already have a copy. The buyer's solicitor typically determines the exact end date, and both parties' solicitors track it closely.</p>

      <p>If the buyer terminates the contract within the cooling-off period, they are entitled to do so without providing a reason. However, the termination comes at a cost. The buyer forfeits 0.25% of the purchase price as a penalty to the seller. On a $1,200,000 property, that is $3,000. The amount is typically held by the real estate agent as deposit and paid to the seller upon termination. This penalty is designed to deter casual use of the right while still giving buyers a genuine exit option in the early stages of a contract.</p>

      <p>If no deposit has been paid, the seller can pursue the buyer for the 0.25% penalty through the courts, though in practice this is rare. Ensuring a deposit is paid at the time of signing is the cleaner outcome for sellers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When the cooling-off period does not apply</h2>
      <p>The most significant exception to the cooling-off period is auction. Residential property sold at auction in Queensland carries no cooling-off right. When the auctioneer's hammer falls and the buyer signs the contract at the auction, that contract is immediately binding. The buyer cannot terminate using the cooling-off provisions because they do not apply. This is one of the structural advantages of selling by auction that is often overlooked when vendors are weighing up methods of sale. It eliminates the 5-business-day window of uncertainty that private treaty contracts carry.</p>

      <p>The cooling-off period also does not apply when the buyer is a corporation (as opposed to an individual), or when the buyer has obtained a certificate from a solicitor waiving the cooling-off right. Solicitor-certified waivers are occasionally requested by sellers who want certainty, particularly in multiple-offer situations where the seller will only consider buyers who are prepared to commit unconditionally. Buyers can choose to provide one, but they cannot be required to.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens to the contract conditions during cooling-off</h2>
      <p>The cooling-off period runs concurrently with, but separately from, any conditions in the contract. A typical private treaty contract in Queensland includes a finance condition (usually 14 to 21 days) and a building and pest inspection condition (often 7 to 14 days). These run from the contract date and give the buyer the right to terminate on specific grounds if those conditions are not satisfied.</p>

      <p>The cooling-off period sits on top of these. A buyer could theoretically terminate within the 5-business-day cooling-off window without needing to cite a failed condition, paying only the 0.25% penalty. Once the cooling-off period expires and the contract is still on foot, the buyer's only remaining termination rights are tied to whether those conditions are met or waived. This is why sellers sometimes hear agents describe the period after cooling-off expires as a firmer contract, the buyer has fewer clean exit points from that point forward.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How agents manage the cooling-off period in practice</h2>
      <p>When a seller accepts an offer in a private treaty campaign, the signed contract is dated and the cooling-off clock starts. Good agents track this date carefully and maintain regular communication with both parties' solicitors to confirm the buyer's position as the cooling-off date approaches.</p>

      <p>Sellers should not treat the cooling-off period as dead time. If you have other interested buyers who did not make the final cut, it is worth your agent maintaining contact with them in case the cooling-off right is exercised. You cannot continue marketing the property as actively available while under contract, but keeping a backup buyer warm is a reasonable precaution in the first five business days.</p>

      <p>For buyers, exercising the cooling-off right is not a decision to take lightly. Beyond the 0.25% financial penalty, there is a reputational consideration. Brisbane's inner-east property market is not large. Agents and vendors talk. A buyer who terminates at cooling-off and then presents an offer on another property through the same agency, or in the same area, may find their offer received with more caution than it otherwise would have been. The cooling-off right exists and buyers are entitled to use it, but doing so without a substantive reason is not without consequence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers need to do during this period</h2>
      <p>As a seller in Queensland, your obligations during the cooling-off period are straightforward. You are bound by the contract. You cannot accept another offer or take the property off the market to remarket it. You are also not entitled to terminate using the cooling-off provisions because the right belongs to the buyer only. If you want to exit the contract as a seller, you need a different legal mechanism entirely, and you should take your solicitor's advice before attempting it.</p>

      <p>The practical implication is that once you sign a contract, your first 5 business days involve some uncertainty about whether the contract will proceed. In a strong market where buyer demand is high, termination during cooling-off is uncommon. In a softer market where buyers are negotiating from a position of more leverage and have multiple properties to consider, it happens more often. Your agent's read on the specific buyer's motivation and financial readiness matters here. A buyer who has already done building and pest, sought legal advice before signing, and paid a meaningful deposit is a lower cooling-off risk than a buyer who signed at the open on a Saturday afternoon without speaking to a solicitor first.</p>

